One feasible path to convert a temperature difference into available electricity is to employ a TEG23,24. The viable TEG modules have been developed and widely utilized in vehicles25, wearable devices26, and industrial waste-heat recovery systems27,28 because of their unique advantages such as no-pollution, small modular availability and non-mechanical vibration29,29. This provides us a reliable approach to reasonably take advantage of the naturally-existed temperature difference between the Sun, the Earth’s topsoil, and the outer ace. Here, we experimentally demonstrate an environment-friendly and cost-effective energy strategy for electricity generation both at the daytime and nighttime based on a TEG module. Such a system can produce a peak power density of 37 mW/m2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
