				\begin{document}$$T_{Air}$$\end{document} (Fig. 4F). The details on the temperature of the top and bottom sides for TEG module in Fig. 4B–F are provided in Fig. S7. Besides increasing the concentration factors and the area ratio of the absorber/emitter over the TEG module, exploring new materials that can be fabricated to be self-adaptive absorber/emitter acting as a selective solar absorber at the daytime and an ideal radiative cooler during the night time will be a promising way to increase the efficiency of a 24-h electricity generation system. Furthermore, thermoelectric materials with a high ZT value around the operating temperature such as 300 K, of such an electricity generation system can be a hot spot from the view of material science. From the device engineering perspectives, depressing the thermal loss from the backside of the absorber/emitter owing to the convection heat transfer between the ambient air and absorber/emitter can increase the temperature difference between the hot side and the cold side of the TEG module during the daytime when the area of the absorber is bigger than that of the TEG module. A similar rule also applies to the scenario in the nighttime. This improvement can weaken the heating from the ambient to the backside of the emitter and thus enlarge the temperature difference between the hot side and the cold side of the TEG module.

This work experimentally validates the possibility of a TEG based energy harvesting system working 24 h continuously through solar heating and radiative cooling by effectively assembling the commercially available and cost-effective TEG components. The prototype of the designed TEG device is prepared by using a high efficient black painted absorber/emitter to absorb the solar energy and harvesting the coldness of the outer space. The soil acts perfectly as a heat sink at daytime, while as a heat source for the nighttime, that resulting in a better performance than the ambient air. Such a system can produce a peak power density of 37 mW/m2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$^2$$\end{document} at night and a peak value of 723 mW/m2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$^2$$\end{document} for the daytime without an energy storage system or no active power input. The corresponding efficiency is 0.0723% and 0.0025% for the daytime and nighttime, respectively. To evaluate the performance of the overall system, a theoretical model has been built to analyze the potential parameters that affect the efficiency of the 24-h energy harvesting system. It reveals that the concentration factor and the area ratio are key design parameters to achieve maximum efficiency. The weather conditions, e.g. relative humidity and cloud thickness, are studied to evaluate the performance of the proposed device. It shows that selective radiative cooler is not always a better option than the black one which is easier to fabricate using the commercial black paints. This approach provides an alternative for electricity generation at both daytime and nighttime without the necessity of the use of the battery storage for the off-grid rural areas. The Sun, the soil, and the outer space are ubiquitous for everyone, that renders it unlimited and unconstrained for the future energy applications.

